",["$r","Note",null,{"children":[["$r","p",null,{"children":["Side effects are a broader term than Effects. Effects specifically refer to code that’s wrapped in ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"useEffect"}],", while a side effect is a general term for code that has any observable effect other than its primary result of returning a value to the caller."]}],["$r","p",null,{"children":["Side effects are typically written inside of ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"/learn/responding-to-events","children":"event handlers"}]," or Effects. But never during render."]}]]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["While render must be kept pure, side effects are necessary at some point in order for your app to do anything interesting, like showing something on the screen! The key point of this rule is that side effects should not run ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"#how-does-react-run-your-code","children":"in render"}],", as React can render components multiple times. In most cases, you’ll use ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"learn/responding-to-events","children":"event handlers"}]," to handle side effects. Using an event handler explicitly tells React that this code doesn’t need to run during render, keeping render pure. If you’ve exhausted all options – and only as a last resort – you can also handle side effects using ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"useEffect"}],"."]}],"
",["$r","h3",null,{"id":"mutation","children":"When is it okay to have mutation? "}],"
",["$r","h4",null,{"id":"local-mutation","children":"Local mutation "}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["One common example of a side effect is mutation, which in JavaScript refers to changing the value of a non-",["$r","a",null,{"href":"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Primitive","target":"_blank","rel":"nofollow noopener noreferrer","children":"primitive"}]," value. In general, while mutation is not idiomatic in React, ",["$r","em",null,{"children":"local"}]," mutation is absolutely fine:"]}],"
",["$r","pre",null,{"children":["$r","code",null,{"className":"language-js","meta":"{2,7}","children":"function FriendList({ friends }) {
  const items = []; // ✅ Good: locally created
  for (let i = 0; i < friends.length; i++) {
    const friend = friends[i];
    items.push(
      <Friend key={friend.id} friend={friend} />
    ); // ✅ Good: local mutation is okay
  }
  return <section>{items}</section>;
}
"}]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["There is no need to contort your code to avoid local mutation. ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map","target":"_blank","rel":"nofollow noopener noreferrer","children":["$r","code",null,{"children":"Array.map"}]}]," could also be used here for brevity, but there is nothing wrong with creating a local array and then pushing items into it ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"#how-does-react-run-your-code","children":"during render"}],"."]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["Even though it looks like we are mutating ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"items"}],", the key point to note is that this code only does so ",["$r","em",null,{"children":"locally"}]," – the mutation isn’t “remembered” when the component is rendered again. In other words, ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"items"}]," only stays around as long as the component does. Because ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"items"}]," is always ",["$r","em",null,{"children":"recreated"}]," every time ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"<FriendList />"}]," is rendered, the component will always return the same result."]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["On the other hand, if ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"items"}]," was created outside of the component, it holds on to its previous values and remembers changes:"]}],"
",["$r","pre",null,{"children":["$r","code",null,{"className":"language-js","meta":"{1,7}","children":"const items = []; // 🔴 Bad: created outside of the component
function FriendList({ friends }) {
