",["$r","p",null,{"children":["A component’s props and state are immutable ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"learn/state-as-a-snapshot","children":"snapshots"}],". Never mutate them directly. Instead, pass new props down, and use the setter function from ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"useState"}],"."]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"You can think of the props and state values as snapshots that are updated after rendering. For this reason, you don’t modify the props or state variables directly: instead you pass new props, or use the setter function provided to you to tell React that state needs to update the next time the component is rendered."}],"
",["$r","h3",null,{"id":"props","children":"Don’t mutate Props "}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"Props are immutable because if you mutate them, the application will produce inconsistent output, which can be hard to debug since it may or may not work depending on the circumstance."}],"
",["$r","pre",null,{"children":["$r","code",null,{"className":"language-js","meta":"{2}","children":"function Post({ item }) {
